## A. Dynamic Buffered Voronoi Cell

We consider the inter-collision-free region that moves along the target's predicted trajectory. We define a Dynamic Buffered Voronoi Cell (DBVC) to avoid collisions between the $i$-th and $j$-th agents as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{H}_{s}^{i j}(t)= & \left\{\mathbf{x}(t) \in \mathbb{R}^{2} \mid\left(\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{j}-\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{i}\right)^{\top}\left(\mathbf{x}(t)-\mathbf{x}_{q}(t)+\mathbf{x}_{q 0}-\right.\right. \\
& \left.\frac{\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{i}+\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{j}}{2}\right)+r_{c}\left\|\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{j}-\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{i}\right\| \leq 0\} \\
\mathcal{H}_{s}^{j i}(t)= & \left\{\mathbf{x}(t) \in \mathbb{R}^{2} \mid\left(\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{i}-\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{j}\right)^{\top}\left(\mathbf{x}(t)-\mathbf{x}_{q}(t)+\mathbf{x}_{q 0}-\right.\right. \\
& \left.\left.\frac{\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{j}+\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{i}}{2}\right)+r_{c}\left\|\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{i}-\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{j}\right\| \leq 0\right\}
\end{aligned}
$$

Lemma 1. If $\mathbf{x}_{c}^{i}(t) \in \mathcal{H}_{s}^{i j}(t)$ and $\mathbf{x}_{c}^{j}(t) \in \mathcal{H}_{s}^{j i}(t), i \neq j \in \mathcal{I}_{c}$, the $i$-th and $j$-th agents do not collide with each other.
Proof. When $\mathbf{x}_{c}^{i}(t) \in \mathcal{H}_{s}^{i j}(t)$ and $\mathbf{x}_{c}^{j}(t) \in \mathcal{H}_{s}^{j i}(t)$, the summation of constraints in (7) yields:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left(\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{i}-\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{j}\right)^{\top}\left(\mathbf{x}_{c}^{i}(t)-\mathbf{x}_{c}^{j}(t)\right)+2 r_{c}\left\|\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{j}-\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{i}\right\| \leq 0 \\
& \Leftrightarrow\left(\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{i}-\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{j}\right)^{\top}\left(\mathbf{x}_{c}^{i}(t)-\mathbf{x}_{c}^{j}(t)\right) \geq 2 r_{c}\left\|\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{i}-\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{j}\right\|
\end{aligned}
$$

By using Cauchy-Schwartz Inequality and (8), we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|\mathbf{x}_{c}^{i}(t)-\mathbf{x}_{c}^{j}(t)\right\| & \geq \frac{\left\|\left(\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{i}-\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{j}\right)^{\top}\left(\mathbf{x}_{c}^{i}(t)-\mathbf{x}_{c}^{j}(t)\right)\right\|}{\left\|\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{i}-\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{j}\right\|} \\
& \geq \frac{2 r_{c}\left\|\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{i}-\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{j}\right\|}{\left\|\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{i}-\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{j}\right\|}=2 r_{c}
\end{aligned}
$$

Hence, we can conclude that $\mathcal{H}_{s}^{i j}(t)$ and $\mathcal{H}_{s}^{j i}(t)$ do not make inter-agent collisions.

## A. Primitive Sampling

Based on the $i$-th agent's current position $\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{i}$ and velocity $\dot{\mathbf{x}}_{c 0}^{i}$, we formulate the following optimal control problem to sample primitives, which can be solved in the closed form.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\min _{\mathbf{u}_{c}^{i}(t)} & \frac{1}{T} \int_{0}^{T}\left\|\mathbf{u}_{c}^{i}(t)\right\|^{2} d t \\
\text { s.t. } & \dot{\mathbf{x}}_{c}^{i}(t)=F_{c} \mathbf{z}_{c}^{i}(t)+G_{c} \mathbf{u}_{c}^{i}(t) \\
& \mathbf{z}_{c}^{i}(t)=\left[\begin{array}{l}
\mathbf{x}_{c}^{i}(t) \\
\dot{\mathbf{x}}_{c}^{i}(t)
\end{array}\right], F_{c}=\left[\begin{array}{ll}
0_{2} & I_{2} \\
0_{2} & 0_{2}
\end{array}\right], G_{c}=\left[\begin{array}{l}
0_{2} \\
I_{2}
\end{array}\right] \\
& \mathbf{x}_{c}^{i}(0)=\mathbf{x}_{c 0}^{i}, \dot{\mathbf{x}}_{c}^{i}(0)=\dot{\mathbf{x}}_{c 0}^{i}, \quad \mathbf{x}_{c}^{i}(T)=\mathbf{x}_{c f}^{i}
\end{aligned}
$$

$0_{2}$ is a $2 \times 2$ zero matrix, and $I_{2}$ is a $2 \times 2$ identity matrix. The $\mathbf{x}_{c f}^{i}$ are terminal points, sampled around the target's terminal points $\mathbf{x}_{q}(T)$ :

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathbf{x}_{c f}^{i}=\mathbf{x}_{q}(T)+\left[r_{c s}^{i} \cos \psi_{c s}^{i}, r_{c s}^{i} \sin \psi_{c s}^{i}\right]^{\top} \\
& r_{c s}^{i} \sim U\left[\underline{r}_{c s}^{i}, \vec{r}_{c s}^{i}\right], \psi_{c s}^{i} \sim U\left[\underline{\psi}_{c s}^{i}, \bar{\psi}_{c s}^{i}\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

$U$ represents the uniform distribution, and $\left(\underline{r}_{c s}^{i}, \bar{r}_{c s}^{i}\right)$ and $\left(\underline{\psi}_{c s}^{i}, \bar{\psi}_{c s}^{i}\right)$ are pairs of the lower and upper bound of distribution of radius and azimuth, respectively.
